INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8dd04dab-bc14-417b-a1d4-5e5220239546',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$DynamoDB Data Modeling — Design for Access Patterns, Not Relations$escape$,
  $escape$DynamoDB punishes normalized schemas. Unlike RDS, there are no JOINs — every query is a single GetItem, Query, or Scan. If your access patterns require three entities, you pay three round trips with normalization. The fix is single-table design: collapse entities into one table using composite keys and overloaded attributes.

Define your access patterns first. For a SaaS app needing 'get all orders for a user' and 'get order by ID', a single table with PK=USER#<userId> / SK=ORDER#<orderId> handles both. A Query on PK fetches all orders; GetItem on both keys fetches one.

Use GSIs (Global Secondary Indexes) as escape hatches for alternate access patterns. Flip the key structure: GSI1PK=ORDER#<orderId>, GSI1SK=USER#<userId> enables lookup by order without scanning.

Denormalize aggressively — duplicate status, username, and timestamps into each item. DynamoDB's write cost is cheap; the read latency you save by avoiding extra fetches is not. Update duplicated data via DynamoDB Streams + Lambda when the source changes.$escape$,
  $escape$import { DynamoDBClient, QueryCommand } from "@aws-sdk/client-dynamodb";

const client = new DynamoDBClient({ region: "us-east-1" });

// Single-table: fetch all orders for a user
const result = await client.send(new QueryCommand({
  TableName: "AppTable",
  KeyConditionExpression: "PK = :pk AND begins_with(SK, :skPrefix)",
  ExpressionAttributeValues: {
    ":pk":       { S: "USER#usr_abc123" },
    ":skPrefix": { S: "ORDER#" },
  },
}));

console.log(result.Items);$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
